00:10:49.750 --> 00:10:53.610 position:56%
The corpus of landscapes was
painted by the leading court painter

00:10:53.610 --> 00:10:59.570
of the Nasiri era Mohammad Ghaffari
Kamal al Mulk, 1859 to 1922,

00:10:59.570 --> 00:11:05.580
who was also the principal exponent
of European-style academic painting

00:11:05.580 --> 00:11:10.580
in the late Qajar and
early Pahlavi eras.

00:11:11.870 --> 00:11:15.580
Kamal al Mulk is perhaps best
known for his portraiture

00:11:15.580 --> 00:11:20.060
and architectural views, but
my current research has led me

00:11:20.060 --> 00:11:26.500
to conclude that he had an abiding
interest in the genre of landscape.

00:11:28.180 --> 00:11:34.120
I will argue that these landscape
paintings present critical new

00:11:34.120 --> 00:11:37.400
evidence for the development
of Kamal al Mulk's [inaudible]

00:11:37.400 --> 00:11:42.170
and that they play a
significant role in the emergence

00:11:42.170 --> 00:11:47.800
of the Iranian landscape of the
late Qajar and early Pahlavi eras.

00:11:47.800 --> 00:11:52.940
A subject which has hitherto
been largely unexplored.

00:11:52.940 --> 00:11:55.910
The works fall into two
chronological groups,

00:11:55.910 --> 00:11:57.210
as you will see.

00:11:57.210 --> 00:12:03.020 position:56%
The first group features four views
of Iranian mountain landscapes dated

00:12:03.020 --> 00:12:08.370
to the 1880's, which are among
his earliest known works.

00:12:08.370 --> 00:12:13.170
The second group is comprised
of two European landscapes,

00:12:13.170 --> 00:12:19.040
which may be assigned to
sometime between 1898 and 1901,

00:12:19.040 --> 00:12:23.330
executed either in
Florence or in Paris,

00:12:23.330 --> 00:12:27.870
both of which he lived
in at that time.

00:12:27.870 --> 00:12:31.340
As a group, the paintings
are remarkably fresh

00:12:31.340 --> 00:12:34.010
and largely unrecorded.

00:12:34.010 --> 00:12:37.220
The landscapes and their
lengthy inscriptions

00:12:37.220 --> 00:12:41.980
by Kamal al Mulk himself--
you can see on the lower left

00:12:41.980 --> 00:12:46.230
or right there are like two,
three lines of inscriptions.

00:12:46.230 --> 00:12:50.730
Giving details of date and
location provide the framework--

00:12:50.730 --> 00:12:53.710
thank you so much--
for our discussion.

00:12:53.710 --> 00:12:57.160
First, I will discuss
Nasiri court culture

00:12:57.160 --> 00:12:59.700
in Kamal al Mulk's
career-- thank you so much.

00:12:59.700 --> 00:13:05.580
Second, I will present an analysis
of Kamal al Mulk's landscapes

00:13:05.580 --> 00:13:13.040
of the 1880's and his post-1900
landscapes and those of his school,

00:13:13.040 --> 00:13:15.210
the [inaudible] Kamal al Mulk.

00:13:15.210 --> 00:13:18.580
And, finally, consider
their significance

00:13:18.580 --> 00:13:23.810
for the Iranian landscape tradition
and the birth of Iranian modernism.

00:13:23.810 --> 00:13:28.350
So, first, Nasiri court
culture, the setting.

00:13:28.350 --> 00:13:34.020
Court culture of the era of
Nassereddin Shah, 1848 to 1896,

00:13:34.020 --> 00:13:39.420 position:56%
was dominated by the will and whims
of the autocratic ruler and centered

00:13:39.420 --> 00:13:44.210
in the Golestan Palace, the
site of a precarious balance

00:13:44.210 --> 00:13:48.450
between Persian tradition
and European modernity.

00:13:48.450 --> 00:13:52.460
Certain features pertain
directly to the production

00:13:52.460 --> 00:13:55.800
of the landscape corpus
under discussion.

00:13:55.800 --> 00:13:58.770
The era was marked
by the introductions

00:13:58.770 --> 00:14:02.000
and enthusiastic acceptance
of photography.

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:07.720
Students were sent abroad to
study, particularly to Paris,

00:14:07.720 --> 00:14:11.920
and a European academy-style
art curriculum was taught

00:14:11.920 --> 00:14:18.370
at the Dar ul-Funun, the royal
military college, as of 1862.

00:14:18.370 --> 00:14:23.160
The role-- the ruler created a
museum for his collection as well

00:14:23.160 --> 00:14:28.110
as designated galleries within
the premises of the palace.

00:14:28.110 --> 00:14:32.230
He founded also an office
of publication and printing

00:14:32.230 --> 00:14:36.310
for a vast program of
historical and scientific texts,

00:14:36.310 --> 00:14:40.440
European translations, and
the Royal Court Gazette.

00:14:40.440 --> 00:14:44.760
These innovations served to
enforce the power of the Shah

00:14:44.760 --> 00:14:48.590
by presenting an image of a
modern and effective ruler

00:14:48.590 --> 00:14:50.870
and by mapping his territories

00:14:50.870 --> 00:14:54.600
and recording information
on his subjects.

00:14:54.600 --> 00:14:59.400
In these endeavors, he was assisted
by a vast array of courtiers

00:14:59.400 --> 00:15:03.340
and ministries, many
of whom were invested

00:15:03.340 --> 00:15:10.160
in introducing European culture,
technology, and eventually reforms.

00:15:10.160 --> 00:15:14.200
These institutions were
accompanied by court activities

00:15:14.200 --> 00:15:19.680 position:56%
such as yearly European-style
exhibitions of artists' work modeled

00:15:19.680 --> 00:15:21.920
on the Salon d'Automne in Paris

00:15:21.920 --> 00:15:25.660
and more traditional
Persian kingly pursuits

00:15:25.660 --> 00:15:30.930
such as court entertainment,
visits to the harem, hunting trips,

00:15:30.930 --> 00:15:34.530
and more rarely military
expeditions.

00:15:34.530 --> 00:15:40.560
The Dar ul-Funun housed both
photographic and painting studios,

00:15:40.560 --> 00:15:42.840
both of which would have been known

00:15:42.840 --> 00:15:48.300
to Kamal al Mulk during his
formative years as a court artist.

00:15:48.300 --> 00:15:53.240
Thousands of photographs produced
for the court have survived.

00:15:53.240 --> 00:15:56.280
Although the portraits and images

00:15:56.280 --> 00:16:04.030
of archeological sites are the
most well-know of the photographs,

00:16:04.030 --> 00:16:09.310
three previously unknown
court stereophotographs,

00:16:09.310 --> 00:16:14.100
of which you see one on the
screen, of the Iranian landscape

00:16:14.100 --> 00:16:18.230
and royal encampments which
were commissioned by the rule

00:16:18.230 --> 00:16:20.280
from the court photographer
[inaudible]

00:16:20.280 --> 00:16:24.400
in the 1860's have
recently been published

00:16:24.400 --> 00:16:27.140
and these you see on the screen.

00:16:27.140 --> 00:16:30.870
The photographs are
inscribed by the ruler

00:16:30.870 --> 00:16:34.350
and by Ali Reza [assumed
spelling] and give the locations

00:16:34.350 --> 00:16:40.180
of [inaudible] and
Aliabad as the sites.

00:16:40.180 --> 00:16:42.770
Unfortunately, further evidence

00:16:42.770 --> 00:16:46.410
from Golestan collections
remains unpublished.

00:16:46.410 --> 00:16:53.010
However, now another very
large corpus of photographs

00:16:53.010 --> 00:16:55.580
and landscape photographs outside

00:16:55.580 --> 00:16:58.980
of Iran has been brought
to my attention.

00:16:58.980 --> 00:17:03.860
The three photographs serve
as intriguing precedents

00:17:03.860 --> 00:17:07.030
for the landscapes
painted by Kamal al Mulk

00:17:07.030 --> 00:17:11.990
with almost photographic
realism in the 1880's.

00:17:11.990 --> 00:17:16.770
More interestingly,
the new photographs,

00:17:16.770 --> 00:17:21.670
which I will discuss again
shortly, are even closer in date

00:17:21.670 --> 00:17:23.890
to Kamal al Mulk's landscapes.

00:17:23.890 --> 00:17:27.800
As you can see, it's dated 1870's.

00:17:27.800 --> 00:17:32.780
Information on landscape painting
at the Dar ul-Funun is sparse

00:17:32.780 --> 00:17:37.090
and we need to open a parenthesis
on the development of this genre

00:17:37.090 --> 00:17:41.110
in Persian painting
before Kamal al Mulk.

00:17:41.110 --> 00:17:43.630
Until the mid-17th century

00:17:43.630 --> 00:17:48.840
when European painting influenced
Persian painting traditions,

00:17:48.840 --> 00:17:54.120
the Persian landscape was
depicted in manuscripts in flat,

00:17:54.120 --> 00:17:57.800
decorative, and semiabstract style.

00:17:57.800 --> 00:18:03.300
Then European-style landscapes
with modeling and recession,

00:18:03.300 --> 00:18:07.390
chiefly associated with the court
painter Mohamad Aman became the

00:18:07.390 --> 00:18:13.180
vogue for manuscript painting and
lacquer work of the 17th century.

00:18:13.180 --> 00:18:18.760
The next development does not
occur until the mid-19th century.

00:18:18.760 --> 00:18:23.160
Landscape backgrounds of Sani'
al-Mulk's watercolor illustrations

00:18:23.160 --> 00:18:28.260
for the Thousand and One
Nights manuscript, about 1853.

00:18:28.260 --> 00:18:33.280
When we see a new infusion of
European painting techniques,

00:18:33.280 --> 00:18:37.740
there may also have been an
awareness of European landscapes

00:18:37.740 --> 00:18:40.860
through the interaction
of Iranian artists

00:18:40.860 --> 00:18:46.980
with European artist diplomats and
officers such as Colonel Colombari

00:18:46.980 --> 00:18:51.220
who flocked to Iran during
the mid- to late-19th century.

00:18:51.220 --> 00:18:56.380
However, the interest
in pure landscape seems

00:18:56.380 --> 00:19:03.000 position:56%
to have been only limited since only
a single painting with a landscape

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:07.290
by Kamal al Mulk's
teacher has survived.

00:19:07.290 --> 00:19:12.270
Kamal al Mulk's Iranian landscapes
would never have been produced

00:19:12.270 --> 00:19:18.040 position:56%
without the ruler's patronage, which
encouraged competition and rivalry

00:19:18.040 --> 00:19:23.060
between bazaar craftsman, court
painters, and photographer.

00:19:23.060 --> 00:19:26.460
Another factor was probably
the publication program

00:19:26.460 --> 00:19:31.050
of Mohammad-Hasan Khan E'temad
al-Saltaneh, the court chronicler

00:19:31.050 --> 00:19:33.690
and chief minister for publication.

00:19:33.690 --> 00:19:36.250
In addition to histories
of the reign,

00:19:36.250 --> 00:19:41.840
the ruler commissioned
historical geographies of Khorasan,

00:19:41.840 --> 00:19:47.080 position:56%
such as the [inaudible] and the most
likely candidate for the context

00:19:47.080 --> 00:19:50.050
of Kamal al Mulk's
Iranian landscape,

00:19:50.050 --> 00:19:55.770
the historical geographic
dictionary, Mirat-ul-Buldan.

00:19:55.770 --> 00:20:01.090
This work was based on
E'temad's data and observation

00:20:01.090 --> 00:20:06.820
of the provinces collected in the
1880's on the order of the Shah.

00:20:06.820 --> 00:20:11.440
As recently noted by Abbas
Amanat, this project was informed

00:20:11.440 --> 00:20:16.250
by a new awareness of
topography and the boundaries

00:20:16.250 --> 00:20:20.950
of Persia as a national entity.

00:20:20.950 --> 00:20:25.790 position:56%
These developments occurred after
the Shah's first two trips to Europe

00:20:25.790 --> 00:20:34.410
in 1873 and 1878 and reflect the
ruler's awareness of the importance

00:20:34.410 --> 00:20:40.010 position:56%
of documenting and controlling his
domains vis a vis those he had seen.

00:20:40.010 --> 00:20:43.820
Kamal al Mulk's ascendency as
a court artist and confidant

00:20:43.820 --> 00:20:47.890
of the ruler would coincide
with these programs.

00:20:47.890 --> 00:20:53.270
So, we will look at his career
from the 1870's to 1901,

00:20:53.270 --> 00:20:56.470
which is the framework
of our paintings.

00:20:56.470 --> 00:20:59.720
Kamal al Mulk was born
in 1859 to a family

00:20:59.720 --> 00:21:03.680
of prominent courtier statesman
and artists from Kashan.

00:21:03.680 --> 00:21:07.830
His early training as an artist
began with apprenticeship

00:21:07.830 --> 00:21:13.060
with his uncle, Abolhassan Ghaffari
Sani' al-Mulk, chief court painter

00:21:13.060 --> 00:21:18.040
of Muhammad and Nassereddin Shahs,
who had received training in Italy

00:21:18.040 --> 00:21:22.550
in classical painting and in the
use of the lithographic press.

00:21:22.550 --> 00:21:26.460
Sani' al-Mulk became a
teacher at the Dar ul-Funun,

00:21:26.460 --> 00:21:29.280 position:56%
where prints of old master paintings

00:21:29.280 --> 00:21:31.610
and plaster casts he
had brought back

00:21:31.610 --> 00:21:34.440
from Europe were part
of the curriculum.

00:21:34.440 --> 00:21:39.630
Sani' al-Mulk was also editor
of the illustrated Court Gazette

00:21:39.630 --> 00:21:43.140
and recipient of major
commissions such as the Thousand

00:21:43.140 --> 00:21:45.170
and One Nights manuscript

00:21:45.170 --> 00:21:49.030
and the [inaudible] wall
paintings of the Nasiri court.

00:21:49.030 --> 00:21:52.120
After the death of
his uncle in 1866,

00:21:52.120 --> 00:21:57.260 position:56%
Kamal al Mulk continued his studies
at the Dar ul-Funun for eight years.

00:21:57.260 --> 00:22:00.550
During the 1870's,
he studied painting

00:22:00.550 --> 00:22:03.950
with Mirza Ali Akbar
Mozayyen-od-Doleh,

00:22:03.950 --> 00:22:08.290
also born in Kashan, who was
Sani' al-Mulk's successor

00:22:08.290 --> 00:22:10.540
at the Dar ul-Funun.

00:22:10.540 --> 00:22:14.950
Mozayyen-od-Doleh was a
graduate or the only graduate

00:22:14.950 --> 00:22:18.190
of the Academie des
Beaux-Arts in Paris,

00:22:18.190 --> 00:22:21.300
which he frequented in the 1850's.

00:22:21.300 --> 00:22:25.200
He faithfully applied the
methods of the French academy

00:22:25.200 --> 00:22:27.800
and probably retained aspects

00:22:27.800 --> 00:22:31.760
of the curriculum already
introduced by Sani' al-Mulk.

00:22:31.760 --> 00:22:34.280
Kamal al Mulk maintained

00:22:34.280 --> 00:22:40.730 position:56%
that Mozayyen-od-Doleh quote unquote
was a trained artist in academic art

00:22:40.730 --> 00:22:47.410
and that quote I learned the art
of painting from no one by myself.

00:22:49.840 --> 00:22:59.060
A still life you see on this
screen dated 1907-8 and a copy

00:22:59.060 --> 00:23:03.370
of the mid-19th century French
artist Rosa Bonheur's iconic

00:23:03.370 --> 00:23:07.630
painting attests to
this artist's skills.

00:23:07.630 --> 00:23:11.600
As evidenced by the landscape
which you see in the background

00:23:11.600 --> 00:23:14.980
of the painting Ploughing Time,

00:23:14.980 --> 00:23:18.500
Mozayyen-od-Doleh's
landscapes were composed after

00:23:18.500 --> 00:23:24.880 position:56%
and closely followed European models
painted in the artist's studio.

00:23:24.880 --> 00:23:30.350
OK? This is very important that
they are copied from other versions

00:23:30.350 --> 00:23:33.160
that were actually
painted in the studio.

00:23:33.160 --> 00:23:39.460
And these confirm Kamal al Mulk's
statement and the originality

00:23:39.460 --> 00:23:42.540
of Kamal al Mulk's
open-air practice,

00:23:42.540 --> 00:23:45.940 position:56%
which you will see in a few minutes.

00:23:45.940 --> 00:23:50.200
Now, Kamal al Mulk's skill soon
caught the attention of the Shah

00:23:50.200 --> 00:23:56.710
who appointed him one of his
personal attendants and, in 1881,

00:23:56.710 --> 00:23:58.090
court painter [inaudible].

00:23:58.090 --> 00:24:03.600
During the following years until
the ruler's assassination in 1896,

00:24:03.600 --> 00:24:08.430
Kamal al Mulk executed portraits
of the ruler, such as you saw

00:24:08.430 --> 00:24:14.370 position:56%
at the beginning, the famous hall of
mirrors, and of the court, palace,

00:24:14.370 --> 00:24:19.050
and of the court notables and
landscape views that surpassed all

00:24:19.050 --> 00:24:24.160
of his contemporary in their
almost photographic naturalism,

00:24:24.160 --> 00:24:27.080
attention to detail,
and color sense.

00:24:27.080 --> 00:24:31.770
His renderings of the hall of
mirrors, the Takiya-ye Dawlat

00:24:31.770 --> 00:24:34.930
and the [inaudible] are
considered among his masterpieces,

00:24:34.930 --> 00:24:38.990
yet he also showed an
interest in genre scenes set

00:24:38.990 --> 00:24:41.270
in contemporary urban settings

00:24:41.270 --> 00:24:45.980
such as his paintings
of geomancers and women.

00:24:45.980 --> 00:24:48.960
Kamal al Mulk appears to
have accompanied the ruler

00:24:48.960 --> 00:24:55.370 position:56%
on his trips throughout the
provinces and this is a major theory

00:24:55.370 --> 00:24:57.940
that we have been developing--

00:24:57.940 --> 00:25:00.940
I've been developing thanks
to this close scrutiny

00:25:00.940 --> 00:25:02.240
of this group of paintings.

00:25:02.240 --> 00:25:06.500 position:56%
So, the idea that Kamal al Mulk
accompanied the ruler throughout the

00:25:06.500 --> 00:25:11.860 position:56%
providence and his landscape and
encampment scenes, which you'll see,

00:25:11.860 --> 00:25:14.270
were executed en plein air.

00:25:14.270 --> 00:25:18.090
The only artist of his
era to have done so.

00:25:18.090 --> 00:25:21.160
Photography did play a
role in his practice,

00:25:21.160 --> 00:25:24.890
particularly in portraiture
and memorial portraits,

00:25:24.890 --> 00:25:29.830
but it was his extraordinary skill
as a painter which is revealed

00:25:29.830 --> 00:25:33.580
in the works he produced in
the decades when he was working

00:25:33.580 --> 00:25:38.260
for the court, including the
landscapes under consideration.

00:25:38.260 --> 00:25:43.230
His great painterly skills were
thus evident even before his trip

00:25:43.230 --> 00:25:46.820
to Europe where he would
study the old masters

00:25:46.820 --> 00:25:49.800
and modern painters directly.

00:25:49.800 --> 00:25:52.810
A year and a half after
the ruler's death,

00:25:52.810 --> 00:25:56.780
Kamal al Mulk requested permission
to go to Europe to study.

00:25:56.780 --> 00:26:00.960
He remained there for a very
long time, for about three years.

00:26:00.960 --> 00:26:05.330
According to his memoirs,
he studied first in Florence

00:26:05.330 --> 00:26:10.790
with the royal portrait
painter Michele Gordigiani,

00:26:10.790 --> 00:26:14.100
who was active until 1909.

00:26:14.100 --> 00:26:17.800
Now, Gordigiani is a
documented painter.

00:26:17.800 --> 00:26:20.880
He was academic in training,
but with a [inaudible]

00:26:20.880 --> 00:26:27.240
for naturalism known in Italy
as the Macchiaioli movement.

00:26:27.240 --> 00:26:32.350
Kamal al Mulk expresses his
admiration for the style

00:26:32.350 --> 00:26:36.640
of naturalism in addition to
his better-known appreciation

00:26:36.640 --> 00:26:39.700
of the old masters in his memoirs.

00:26:39.700 --> 00:26:43.000
Now, as a parenthesis,
what was naturalism?

00:26:43.000 --> 00:26:46.440
It was a mid- to late-19th
century European cultural

00:26:46.440 --> 00:26:50.230
and literary movement which
originated in France with the works

00:26:50.230 --> 00:26:56.360
of Emile Zola and included painters
such as Courbet at the beginning.

00:26:56.360 --> 00:27:01.990 position:56%
It was contemporary with
impressionism and it espoused a form

00:27:01.990 --> 00:27:08.920 position:56%
of heightened realism with social
political awareness that was lacking

00:27:08.920 --> 00:27:12.260
in the light-hearted
scenes of picnics

00:27:12.260 --> 00:27:16.550
and open-air entertainments
favored by the impressionists.

00:27:16.550 --> 00:27:21.810
So, given Kamal al Mulk's
support of the constitutionalists,

00:27:21.810 --> 00:27:27.440
the [foreign phrase] or
intellectuals and of freemasonry,

00:27:27.440 --> 00:27:29.660
it seemed logical he would be drawn

00:27:29.660 --> 00:27:32.250
to this movement, which
he encountered.

00:27:32.250 --> 00:27:34.490
Now, back to Gordigiani.

00:27:34.490 --> 00:27:39.730
He was the official Italian court
painter and although he seems

00:27:39.730 --> 00:27:44.540
to have appreciated Kamal al
Mulk's talents, he also abused it,

00:27:44.540 --> 00:27:48.480
according to the painter
who claimed in his memoirs

00:27:48.480 --> 00:27:56.300
that Gordigiani passed off as his
own work this portrait of the ruler

00:27:56.300 --> 00:28:00.180
of Siam, which was actually
painted by Kamal al Mulk.

00:28:00.180 --> 00:28:04.660 position:56%
And, believe it or not, my assistant
actually located this painting

00:28:04.660 --> 00:28:05.960
on the internet.

00:28:05.960 --> 00:28:07.380
We have no idea where it is,

00:28:07.380 --> 00:28:11.930
but the idea that there is a
Kamal al Mulk original out there

00:28:11.930 --> 00:28:16.490
that I don't know who signed it,
I assume it has the signature

00:28:16.490 --> 00:28:19.280
of Gordigiani in it,
but in his memoirs,

00:28:19.280 --> 00:28:22.410
Kamal al Mulk says
that he painted this.

00:28:22.410 --> 00:28:27.390
So, those are the vagaries of
being a student of a great master.

00:28:27.390 --> 00:28:31.120
After a year and a half,
Kamal al Mulk went on to Paris

00:28:31.120 --> 00:28:35.610
where he rented a studio in the
artist's quarter and copied works

00:28:35.610 --> 00:28:40.180
of the old masters such as
Rembrandt and Titian in the Louvre.

00:28:40.180 --> 00:28:45.020
He also copied Italian
landscapes and executed portraits

00:28:45.020 --> 00:28:48.230
of his fellow artists such
as Henri Fantin-Latour,

00:28:48.230 --> 00:28:52.980 position:56%
the French realist painter, and a
series of remarkable self-portraits.

00:28:52.980 --> 00:28:59.710 position:56%
His main achievement, in my view, in
Europe was to perfect his knowledge

00:28:59.710 --> 00:29:03.530
of the techniques of illusionistic
painting, which he had learned

00:29:03.530 --> 00:29:07.700
through his own practice
in Iran previously,

00:29:07.700 --> 00:29:11.570
and to familiarize himself
with the theories on naturalism

00:29:11.570 --> 00:29:17.160
and literature and art, which were
in vogue in that time in Europe.

00:29:17.160 --> 00:29:20.700
Although Kamal al Mulk worked
as a court painter for a year,

00:29:20.700 --> 00:29:25.210
on his return to Iran, he did
not like Mozaffar ad-Din Shah

00:29:25.210 --> 00:29:29.850
or his questionable taste in art,
so Kamal al Mulk retired himself

00:29:29.850 --> 00:29:33.250
to Baghdad and Karbala
for over two years.

00:29:33.250 --> 00:29:37.390
It is from this period that a
shift in subject matter occurs

00:29:37.390 --> 00:29:41.950
with greater attention paid
to urban scenes and images

00:29:41.950 --> 00:29:45.170
of the everyday life
of ordinary people.

00:29:45.170 --> 00:29:48.770
This represented a major
evolution in the visual language

00:29:48.770 --> 00:29:52.410
of Persian painting and
would have a lasting effect

00:29:52.410 --> 00:29:54.750
on its subsequent development.

00:29:54.750 --> 00:29:59.470
The following analysis will discuss
the role of landscape painting

00:29:59.470 --> 00:30:03.940
in the chronological
evolution of his practice

00:30:03.940 --> 00:30:08.510
and highlight the significance
of this new genre, landscape,

00:30:08.510 --> 00:30:11.500
for modern Iranian painting.

00:30:11.500 --> 00:30:17.540
The first group of mountainous
landscape was painted circa 1882

00:30:17.540 --> 00:30:26.130
and 1883, but I've not made a
finalized reading of all the dates.

00:30:26.130 --> 00:30:29.590
These years coincide with
Kamal al Mulk's early years

00:30:29.590 --> 00:30:31.500
as a court artist.

00:30:31.500 --> 00:30:36.320
Analysis of the iconography,
topography, and inscriptions

00:30:36.320 --> 00:30:41.060
of these works confirm they
were most likely executed

00:30:41.060 --> 00:30:45.950 position:56%
when he accompanied the ruler on
his frequent trips to the provinces.

00:30:45.950 --> 00:30:51.310
The inscriptions provide many
locations from the area of Tehran

00:30:51.310 --> 00:30:57.530
and Mazandaran and I want to thank
my research assistant Layah Bigdeli

00:30:57.530 --> 00:31:02.370
for creating this map of all
the locations of his paintings.

00:31:02.370 --> 00:31:05.790
The inscriptions, which
conform in style with those

00:31:05.790 --> 00:31:08.220
of his other published
inscribed works,

00:31:08.220 --> 00:31:11.740
do not specifically
mention a royal commission.

00:31:11.740 --> 00:31:13.790
Meaning there is never the
phrase [foreign language].

00:31:13.790 --> 00:31:17.790
OK? To the order of.

00:31:17.790 --> 00:31:22.960
However, numerous trips by the
ruler to this area are recorded

00:31:22.960 --> 00:31:28.310
by E'temad al-Saltaneh in his daily
journal by year, day, and month.

00:31:28.310 --> 00:31:31.190
So, the entries coincide
approximately

00:31:31.190 --> 00:31:36.040
with the locations given in the
works themselves, which is--

00:31:36.040 --> 00:31:41.260 position:56%
yes, it's like a goldmine for an
art historian to be able to do that.

00:31:41.260 --> 00:31:46.520
So, all the works are
painted in rectangular format

00:31:46.520 --> 00:31:51.440
from a high viewpoint which
would provide a panoramic view

00:31:51.440 --> 00:31:54.680
of the valley and of the mountains.

00:31:54.680 --> 00:31:58.460
In order to analyze the
relationship between photography

00:31:58.460 --> 00:32:03.700
and Kamal al Mulk's practice,
comparison with the larger corpus

00:32:03.700 --> 00:32:08.630
of landscape photographs from
the previously mentioned private

00:32:08.630 --> 00:32:12.170
collection and from the
Golestan is needed, but--

00:32:12.170 --> 00:32:15.420
which is beyond the
parameters of today's talk.

00:32:15.420 --> 00:32:22.890
So, what I've done is with a single
comparison between this image

00:32:22.890 --> 00:32:29.080
and this early photograph, these
are both views of the same site

00:32:29.080 --> 00:32:32.030
and this we know from
reading the inscriptions.

00:32:32.030 --> 00:32:36.360
A location called Kayvan Shokoh
[assumed spelling], an encampment.

00:32:36.360 --> 00:32:39.300 position:56%
So, you see Kamal al Mulk's painting

00:32:39.300 --> 00:32:43.490
and the photograph
of the same location.

00:32:43.490 --> 00:32:48.770
We see how his choice
differentiates his work

00:32:48.770 --> 00:32:53.030
from the published images taken
by the court photographers.

00:32:53.030 --> 00:32:58.320
You can see the photographs
are square format close ups

00:32:58.320 --> 00:33:03.340
of anecdotal scenes with
the landscape barely visible

00:33:03.340 --> 00:33:04.640
in the background.

00:33:04.640 --> 00:33:07.570
So, a completely different
approach and concern

00:33:07.570 --> 00:33:08.870
from that of the painter.

00:33:08.870 --> 00:33:16.150 position:56%
The compositions are dominated by
rolling hills and mountain foothills

00:33:16.150 --> 00:33:21.060 position:56%
in the background and feature
verdant valleys in the middle ground

00:33:21.060 --> 00:33:25.500
and dark, rocky outcrops
in the foreground.

00:33:25.500 --> 00:33:29.980
Three of the paintings
show large tent encampments

00:33:29.980 --> 00:33:31.700
in the middle ground.

00:33:31.700 --> 00:33:34.520
The scale of the encampments
and the presence

00:33:34.520 --> 00:33:39.860 position:56%
of red textile partitions separating
off the main tent indicate these are

00:33:39.860 --> 00:33:42.860
royal encampments.

00:33:42.860 --> 00:33:45.540
The View of the Bend on the
River, which you see here,

00:33:45.540 --> 00:33:50.490
features a wandering river and
groups of trees on the hillsides

00:33:50.490 --> 00:33:56.570
as well as small retainers in black
in the foreground and a mule train

00:33:56.570 --> 00:33:59.300
which gives scale to
the whole scene.

00:33:59.300 --> 00:34:05.260
A View of [inaudible] depicts
a small village clinging

00:34:05.260 --> 00:34:09.570
to the mountainside with an
[inaudible] in the foreground

00:34:09.570 --> 00:34:13.430
and gardens and houses
in the very front.

00:34:15.770 --> 00:34:20.890
As a rule, the foreground acts
as a repertoire and the rules

00:34:20.890 --> 00:34:25.700
of landscape recession, modeling,
perspective, aerial recession,

00:34:25.700 --> 00:34:29.450
and the direction of light
are faithfully observed

00:34:29.450 --> 00:34:32.140
in the artist's treatment
of the hills.

00:34:32.140 --> 00:34:34.550
Careful attention is paid

00:34:34.550 --> 00:34:38.100
to detailed rendering
also of vegetation.

00:34:38.100 --> 00:34:41.420
Sometimes green and
dotted with trees.

00:34:41.420 --> 00:34:44.060
Sometimes arid and craggy.

00:34:44.060 --> 00:34:47.090
And to do the texture
of the rough earth.

00:34:47.090 --> 00:34:52.450
The contrast between green
and arid areas is typical

00:34:52.450 --> 00:34:56.710
of the Iranian landscape
between Tehran and the Caspian,

00:34:56.710 --> 00:35:02.610
a favorite area for picnicking
and more prolonged country stays.

00:35:02.610 --> 00:35:05.080
The palette is also earthy.

00:35:05.080 --> 00:35:10.460
Terracotta and olive green
shot through with white.

00:35:10.460 --> 00:35:15.340
Crystal clear blue is used
for the water and the sky.

00:35:15.340 --> 00:35:20.460
The minute white tents with
their pointed tops are scattered

00:35:20.460 --> 00:35:24.590
across the landscape as so many
exclamation points is our small

00:35:24.590 --> 00:35:26.680
black figures and animals.

00:35:26.680 --> 00:35:32.290 position:56%
The paintings have a roughly
sketchy surface, not highly polished

00:35:32.290 --> 00:35:37.320
and finished, as if the artist
wanted to capture the immediacy

00:35:37.320 --> 00:35:40.260
and specificity of his experience.

00:35:40.260 --> 00:35:42.770
This is confirmed by
the inscriptions

00:35:42.770 --> 00:35:46.450
which give the exact direction
of the artist's viewpoint.

00:35:46.450 --> 00:35:48.880
This is so remarkable.

00:35:48.880 --> 00:35:52.580
He says it's taken from the north,
it shows the east and the west,

00:35:52.580 --> 00:35:53.980
it's the view through this valley.

00:35:53.980 --> 00:35:55.850 position:56%
So, these inscriptions-- the reading

00:35:55.850 --> 00:35:58.730
of these inscriptions
is very critical.

00:35:58.730 --> 00:36:03.370 position:56%
The careful realism and photographic
details suggest these paintings may

00:36:03.370 --> 00:36:07.050
have had a scientific or
illustrative purpose linked

00:36:07.050 --> 00:36:10.680
to the ruler's previously
discussed policy of recording

00:36:10.680 --> 00:36:12.660
and surveying his domains

00:36:12.660 --> 00:36:15.700
and to E'temad al-Saltaneh's
numerous publications.

00:36:15.700 --> 00:36:18.280
This is entirely theoretical,
but we need--

00:36:18.280 --> 00:36:22.590
we need to have some theory here.

00:36:22.590 --> 00:36:26.430
Now, let us review the
evidence of this group in light

00:36:26.430 --> 00:36:29.540
of the artist's known
landscape [inaudible].

00:36:29.540 --> 00:36:33.430
With this discovery, four new
works are added to the corpus

00:36:33.430 --> 00:36:38.190
of 37 landscapes currently
known and these are all listed--

00:36:38.190 --> 00:36:42.790
I wrote a joint article with
Ahmad Ashraf on Kamal al Mulk

00:36:42.790 --> 00:36:44.620
in the Encyclopedia Iranica.

00:36:44.620 --> 00:36:47.930
Dr. Ashraf really did
the very hard work

00:36:47.930 --> 00:36:51.380
of listing almost every
known work of Kamal al Mulk.

00:36:51.380 --> 00:36:54.880
For those of you who
would like to go further.

00:36:54.880 --> 00:36:59.110
So, at that point, there
were 37 landscapes.

00:36:59.110 --> 00:37:04.200
So, now we added four more
to these, plus another six.

00:37:04.200 --> 00:37:08.450
The four works we just discussed
in conjunction with a few others

00:37:08.450 --> 00:37:11.100
from the decades before
Kamal al Mulk went

00:37:11.100 --> 00:37:15.840
to Europe illustrate the
painter's increasing skill

00:37:15.840 --> 00:37:18.600
in composition in painting
technique.

00:37:18.600 --> 00:37:23.210
So, you can see the artist learning
and teaching himself and get--

00:37:23.210 --> 00:37:26.950
this is 1888, about four years
later than the early ones,

00:37:26.950 --> 00:37:31.330
and you can really see the
amazing progress he's made.

00:37:31.330 --> 00:37:36.630
By the late 1880's, Kamal al Mulk's
landscape become more monumental

00:37:36.630 --> 00:37:40.440
and awe-inspiring, not
unlike the paintings

00:37:40.440 --> 00:37:44.520
of the Hudson River School
capturing the majesty

00:37:44.520 --> 00:37:47.920
of the Alborz mountain
range and the sharp contrast

00:37:47.920 --> 00:37:50.650
with the plains and plateaus below.

00:37:50.650 --> 00:37:56.960
By 1891, his focus has turned to
the human element in the landscape.

00:37:56.960 --> 00:37:59.340
In his depiction of
a tent encampment,

00:37:59.340 --> 00:38:01.090
which you see on the screen,

00:38:01.090 --> 00:38:05.000
which pre-stages the artist's
more naturalistic approach

00:38:05.000 --> 00:38:07.560
after his return from Europe.

00:38:07.560 --> 00:38:12.440
I now turn to the two
Italianate landscapes

00:38:12.440 --> 00:38:15.720
which share sufficient
features to have been painted

00:38:15.720 --> 00:38:18.460
at the same time and place.

00:38:18.460 --> 00:38:28.190
One is signed and dated
1898-99, [inaudible] 1316,

00:38:28.190 --> 00:38:30.250
and the other bears an inscription.

00:38:30.250 --> 00:38:33.660
A very interesting inscription
which states it was copied

00:38:33.660 --> 00:38:37.580
from an Italian painting
and given in exchange

00:38:37.580 --> 00:38:39.250
for a work to another painter.

00:38:39.250 --> 00:38:42.910
So, his inscriptions are
incredibly chatty and informative

00:38:42.910 --> 00:38:46.450
about even the relations
between artists and none

00:38:46.450 --> 00:38:51.290
of this is currently known or
recorded in the study of his work.

00:38:51.290 --> 00:38:56.140
This episode between painters could
have occurred in either Florence

00:38:56.140 --> 00:39:01.690
or Paris since the dates
bridge the time in both cities.

00:39:01.690 --> 00:39:05.980
Stylistically, the
paintings share many feature

00:39:05.980 --> 00:39:10.530
with Jean-Baptiste Camille
Corot, whose work you see

00:39:10.530 --> 00:39:15.170
on the screen compared
with Kamal al Mulk's work.

00:39:15.170 --> 00:39:21.840
Italian landscapes by Corot
such-- and you see, as I said,

00:39:21.840 --> 00:39:25.880
the comparison is when
Corot visited Italy.

00:39:25.880 --> 00:39:31.680 position:56%
And you see similarities such as the
focus on the bridges and aqueducts,

00:39:31.680 --> 00:39:36.910
the style of the houses, the
flat treatment of the surface,

00:39:36.910 --> 00:39:38.480
and the attention to light.

00:39:38.480 --> 00:39:40.890
These are all new.

00:39:40.890 --> 00:39:45.270
However, an exact model remains
to be identified, but I haven't

00:39:45.270 --> 00:39:50.090
yet gone through every single one
of Corot's thousands of paintings,

00:39:50.090 --> 00:39:53.980
so I'm still hopeful,
but this is very close.

00:39:53.980 --> 00:39:57.900
The prototype could also
have been, we must admit,

00:39:57.900 --> 00:40:01.430
by a later Italian
follower of Corot's style.

00:40:01.430 --> 00:40:07.720 position:56%
Although Corot was active earlier in
the 19th century than Kamal al Mulk,

00:40:07.720 --> 00:40:11.790
he was still extremely popular
at the turn of the century

00:40:11.790 --> 00:40:15.740
and would have been held up to
the painter as a worthy model

00:40:15.740 --> 00:40:20.180
of western landscape
painting to emulate.

00:40:20.180 --> 00:40:24.090
As was the case with
the four previous works,

00:40:24.090 --> 00:40:28.380
the two Italian landscape--
and here is the second one--

00:40:28.380 --> 00:40:33.620 position:56%
I have identified this as an Italian
landscape based on the vegetation

00:40:33.620 --> 00:40:37.290
and the presence of the
church in the middle ground.

00:40:37.290 --> 00:40:42.220
They also document a key moment
in Kamal al Mulk's evolution.

00:40:42.220 --> 00:40:44.390
After his European trip,

00:40:44.390 --> 00:40:49.350
he continued to paint
landscapes until the 1920's.

00:40:49.350 --> 00:40:54.640
There are-- these are
considerably looser in brush work

00:40:54.640 --> 00:40:59.260
with a softer palette
and so fused with light

00:40:59.260 --> 00:41:02.330
and air compared to
his earlier attempts.

00:41:02.330 --> 00:41:07.240
The two Italian landscapes
illustrate just how he got there.

00:41:07.240 --> 00:41:09.140
How do we get from here to there?

00:41:09.140 --> 00:41:15.760
We may now asset that in all Kamal
al Mulk painted over 42 landscapes,

00:41:15.760 --> 00:41:20.810
a considerable portion of his
[inaudible] throughout his career.

00:41:20.810 --> 00:41:25.170
Now we pass finally to
the last part of my talk,

00:41:25.170 --> 00:41:29.090
the invention of an
Iranian landscape.

00:41:29.090 --> 00:41:32.420
The introduction and
development of the new genre

00:41:32.420 --> 00:41:36.970
of European-style landscape
painting is a neglected aspect

00:41:36.970 --> 00:41:41.190
of Kamal al Mulk's contribution
to modern Iranian art.

00:41:41.190 --> 00:41:47.030
The importance of his legacy,
which can be seen in the works

00:41:47.030 --> 00:41:51.260
of his followers who studied
with him at the famous school

00:41:51.260 --> 00:41:55.320
that Kamal al Mulk directed
for a very long time

00:41:55.320 --> 00:41:57.470
in the early 20th century.

00:41:57.470 --> 00:42:01.680
And, principally, Ali
Mohammad Heydarian.

00:42:01.680 --> 00:42:09.960 position:56%
Here on the screen, you see a work
by Ghaffari and a work by Heydarian.

00:42:09.960 --> 00:42:15.110
It is worth noting that
besides Kamal al Mulk's school,

00:42:15.110 --> 00:42:17.780
which again you see--
with this comparison,

00:42:17.780 --> 00:42:20.600
you can see how much
influence Heydarian

00:42:20.600 --> 00:42:27.090 position:56%
and how closely he followed him--
besides the school of Kamal al Mulk,

00:42:27.090 --> 00:42:31.070
there was also some
proponents of the school

00:42:31.070 --> 00:42:35.960
of Europeanate [phonetic] landscape
style, but this time channeled

00:42:35.960 --> 00:42:40.250
through Russian 19th
century painting.

00:42:40.250 --> 00:42:43.640
This was passed on
by the Rashti artist

00:42:43.640 --> 00:42:47.690
and teacher Sayed Mohammed Habib
Mohammedi [assumed spelling]

00:42:47.690 --> 00:42:51.500
and by another painter, Hod
Hussain Rasadi [assumed spelling]

00:42:51.500 --> 00:42:55.460
to a new generation of artists
who were to become the pioneers

00:42:55.460 --> 00:43:00.810
of modernism, such as [inaudible],
Nikzad Nojoomi, and [inaudible]

00:43:00.810 --> 00:43:04.610
who were all students of Mohammedi.

00:43:04.610 --> 00:43:09.960 position:56%
In conclusion, Kamal al Mulk's early
landscape paintings may be seen

00:43:09.960 --> 00:43:13.130
as part of experiments
and documentation

00:43:13.130 --> 00:43:18.790
for the court enterprise of
recording and presenting an image

00:43:18.790 --> 00:43:24.710
of Qajar Iran, an image based on,
they thought, empirical evidence.

00:43:24.710 --> 00:43:28.430
When viewed in conjunction with
his later landscape paintings,

00:43:28.430 --> 00:43:32.060
they also reveal to
be-- Kamal al Mulk

00:43:32.060 --> 00:43:36.520
to be the truly innovative
artist he claimed to be.

00:43:36.520 --> 00:43:42.010
So, I view even artist's memoirs
with skepticism, but, in this case,

00:43:42.010 --> 00:43:47.490
we I think confirm that indeed
how innovative he was early

00:43:47.490 --> 00:43:48.790
in his career.

00:43:48.790 --> 00:43:51.450
The only known painter
of his generation

00:43:51.450 --> 00:43:55.580
to compose his paintings outside
the studio is really remarkable.

00:43:55.580 --> 00:44:00.190
Equally important, the
Italianate works form a bridge

00:44:00.190 --> 00:44:05.830
to his later landscapes using
a more modern visual language.

00:44:05.830 --> 00:44:09.560
Hopefully we have advanced
our understanding

00:44:09.560 --> 00:44:13.710
of later Persian painting and
its art historical issues.

00:44:13.710 --> 00:44:18.640
These paintings are key works in
the evolution of Kamal al Mulk

00:44:18.640 --> 00:44:23.550
from academic painting for the
court to naturalist paining

00:44:23.550 --> 00:44:29.850
of Iranian modern life which was
to have the most profound influence

00:44:29.850 --> 00:44:33.850 position:56%
on the course of Iranian modern art.

00:44:33.850 --> 00:44:41.790 position:56%
The formation of Iranian modern art
involved not only European stylistic

00:44:41.790 --> 00:44:46.330
and iconographic conventions,
but the introduction

00:44:46.330 --> 00:44:51.080
of new subject matter and genre
such as the realistic portrait

00:44:51.080 --> 00:44:55.740
and what we've been discussing
today, the independent landscapes;

00:44:55.740 --> 00:44:58.770
both of which would
have been impossible

00:44:58.770 --> 00:45:01.400 position:56%
without the genius of Kamal al Mulk.

00:45:01.400 --> 00:45:03.200
Thank you.

00:45:03.200 --> 00:45:12.460
[ Applause ]

00:45:12.460 --> 00:45:13.760
&gt;&gt; Hirad Dinavari:
Thank you, Dr. Diba.

00:45:13.760 --> 00:45:15.230
