00:46:03.570 --> 00:46:08.000
but it's interesting, as
I said, when he had the--

00:46:08.000 --> 00:46:13.370
he was no longer an official court
painter that he went to Karbala

00:46:13.370 --> 00:46:19.130
and Najaf and he painted
scenes of those modest towns

00:46:19.130 --> 00:46:20.520
and squares and the people.

00:46:20.520 --> 00:46:23.390
So, he began going
beyond the parameters

00:46:23.390 --> 00:46:27.560
of the court certainly by 1900.

00:46:27.560 --> 00:46:30.630
And this continued much more
strongly after he returned

00:46:30.630 --> 00:46:33.610
from Europe and I think
this broadening

00:46:33.610 --> 00:46:40.270
of subject matter beyond the court
to a more modern kind of interest

00:46:40.270 --> 00:46:44.610
in the-- in his own time.

00:46:44.610 --> 00:46:48.560
I think you see it evolving
and it becomes much stronger

00:46:48.560 --> 00:46:50.240
in the early 20th century.

00:46:50.240 --> 00:46:54.660
So, yes, there are many,
many urban city views.

00:46:54.660 --> 00:46:57.680
Yes. Her Majesty.

00:46:57.680 --> 00:47:03.000
&gt;&gt; Farah Pahlavi: Didn't he paint
also a lot of people and musicians?

00:47:03.000 --> 00:47:04.300
&gt;&gt; Layla Diba: Oh, yes.

00:47:04.300 --> 00:47:09.090
Yes, yes. I mean his-- he's
primarily known for his portraiture

00:47:09.090 --> 00:47:13.050
and they're remarkable,
the court musicians,

00:47:13.050 --> 00:47:17.360
the court personalities,
and they're so incisive.

00:47:17.360 --> 00:47:20.340
People, you know, mention
photography

00:47:20.340 --> 00:47:22.430
because they're so realistic.

00:47:22.430 --> 00:47:25.990
I think the most interesting
things he did was a series

00:47:25.990 --> 00:47:29.230
of self-portraits, which
again was completely--

00:47:29.230 --> 00:47:34.250 position:56%
no Iranian painter ever had the
temerity to use himself as a subject

00:47:34.250 --> 00:47:36.430
and there are like
six self-portraits

00:47:36.430 --> 00:47:38.980
and he greatly admired Rembrandt.

00:47:38.980 --> 00:47:43.670 position:56%
So, I think, you know, his interest
in portraiture once he got to Europe

00:47:43.670 --> 00:47:46.270
and the Louvre-- and
you saw Rembrandts,

00:47:46.270 --> 00:47:51.210
but his skill as a painter-- and I
think he was interested in humanity

00:47:51.210 --> 00:47:56.860
and personality and many of his
greatest works are portraits.

00:47:56.860 --> 00:47:58.160
Absolutely.

00:47:58.160 --> 00:47:59.460
Thank you.

00:47:59.460 --> 00:48:00.760
Yes, please.

00:48:00.760 --> 00:48:03.610 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Farah Pahlavi: You know, because
